I got this one by a trade as a raw MPEG2 file and it has been on my things-to-do list for a while, but now I can check this one off and I thought let's put it up here. Below all the info that came with the trade DVD.


------------------------------------------------------------------------
Beastie Boys live in concert at Loreley in Germany 1998 (original TV broadcast from WDR Rockpalast)

The raw MPEG2 video file was grabbed from an old VHS-tape: sound is great (stereo) but the video quality has some noise. This is the original recording from June 20th 1998: songs 16 - 29 were broadcasted live on TV, after that they re-broadcasted the beginning of the concert, that is the reason why this playlist is some kind of mixed up.

Bon Jovi

Rio de Janeiro, Brazil
Pro-Shot Upgrade

Video Format: NTSC

Mpeg 2
720 X 480
4290.8 kbps constant


Audio Format: Dolby AC-3

The actual lineage is unknown but it is suspected that this is from a station master - it's that good. See screenshots.

This is being torrented by me but the content of this upload is credited to Bonjovi90 who sent it to me and asked for it to be shared here.  All thanks should go to him - he certainly has mine.

There is a misconception that this concert was played in Maracana Stadium.  It was not. It was at Praa da Apoteose in Rio at the Hollywood Rock Festival. See the comments by people who were actually there, in the thread still on the tracker (link below).

There are several other good versions of this concert available.  There is Big Hot Night which has lossless audio and there is the Japanese TV WOW version which has slightly better video than Big Hot Night but only 192 kbps audio.

The Japanese WOW version is still on the tracker and can be found here:

http://www.dimeadozen.org/torrents-details.php?id=180165

Neither of the above versions hold a candle to the video quality of this one.  It is quite simply stunning - especially for a video this old.

This is probably about as good as it's going to get for this show.  A big thank you to Dominik for sharing this with all of us - I'm just providing the bandwidth :)

This is one of the "IN CONCERT" programs the BBC did in the early 70's. The format was a studio, artists playing acoustic (or what we would call "unplugged" nowadays!), and a small audience. I know there is a version of this concert circulating with on the same dvd James Taylor and Neil Young (NTSC) and The Kinks, The Eagles, Elton John, and Neil Diamond (PAL). There is also a compilation DVD of Cat Stevens which contains this concert. This version is IMO an upgrade to these.
Because of the fact that db.etree etc. has different dates listed for this concert, I left the day and month of this concert unspecified.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pha_Vr8eS7w&feature=channel_page


Notes:

What a great feeling capturing this great band after 11 years of absence.
A Band like a good wine, maturing and tasting better with time.
Seriously download listeners didn't know what hit them. Bands like korn, limp bizkit & other "extreme bands" sounded
nothing like the mighty FNM. It was time for the kings to be on stage once more.

A HD cam was used to capture this performance and later the webcast DSBD audio was added.
There is a 5.1 audio stream using both the DSBD and the cam audio to give a more "live" feeling to the watching experience.

The HD master file was downconverted to SD DVD version as the intention of this release was to be accessible to as many people
as possible.

The HD/Blu-Ray Master files can be given to people who will hit the record button and film this awesome band.

Enjoy!

REVIEW:
This DVD features the entire show in pro-shot quality as well as a pre-show interview with the band which cuts in. There are clear shots of the band throughout, mainly focusing on Dave and the picture quality itself is very good with no visible macroblocking thanks to a high bitrate transfer. The picture is clear with no interference although it is slighlty soft overall. The audio is clear and punchy thanks to a linear PCM track with no real issues. 

The disc has a menu with chapter points for each song and there are no extras on the DVD.

SETLIST:
 All My Life
 Breakout
 Times Like These
 Learn to Fly
 Everlong

 All My Life
 Generator
 My Hero
 Have It All
 Disenchanted Lullabye
 Enough Space
 Aurora
 Stacked Actors
 Low
 Monkey Wrench
 Everlong

(First five tracks are 2002/09/12, track 6 onwards is 2003/05/01)

REVIEW:
This DVD contains broadcasts of two different shows from Japanese TV. The first is a direct DVB recording of the September 12th 2002 show in Tokyo, Japan. Only five songs are featured but the recording is very high quality, a high bitrate DVB broadcast captured directly with a standalone recorder. The picture is sharp and clear with no macroblocking or other artifacts. Audio is also clear and crisp, making for a very nice pro-shot video. 

The second broadcast is again from Japan but of a show in the US, at the Black Cat in May, 2003. Some songs from the acoustic portion of this show is featured on the Everywhere But Home but this broadcast features songs from the electric set. This is a VHS recording rather than a direct digital copy but is still of quite good quality, with only a little fuzzyness in the picture. The audio is well mixed and again nice and clear.

Text of original seed:
The Jimi Hendrix Experience
Live in Stockholm, Sweden 
Jan.9, 1969 
(Klipped Records DVD 5.01 / - / DVD-R)

(Stora Salen, Konserthuset, Stockholm 09.01.69 [Complete 1st Show] + filler: "Popside", Radiohuset, Stockholm 24.05.67) Master Videotape > S-VHS > DVD except 1967 footage *
[* Complete lineage: 09.01.69: Pro open reel video> (possibly pro video cassette)> S-VHS video (3D-DNR/TBC + Super Picture)>DVD-R (XP (1 hour) mode) / 24.05.67: ?? mm film>Pro video>S-VHS video (3D-DNR/TBC + Super Picture)>DVD-R (XP (1 hour) mode)]
notes:
- Provided info (edited): "The Videotapes from Radiohuset 1967 and Koncerthuset 1969 are copied directly from the video recordings / video tapes in SR's archives to Super VHS tapes. The DVDs have later been made from these Super VHS tapes. The 1969 concert was long believed to have been lost, and wasn't officially re-discovered until 2005. The Super VHS copy this particular DVD is made from, was however made from the same tape 4-5 years earlier. These recordings are as good as they'll get. There are 3 short flaws on the Konserthuset recording, but these are on SVT's original tape as well, and have not been introduced during the transfer to Super VHS. The flaws in question are at the end of "Fire" (43), at the end of "Red House" (37) and at the end of "Sunshine Of Your Love" (17), at which points the picture gets a little shaky for about 1/2 second each time."
- By far the best available version of the Stockholm 09.01.69 footage (Upgrade of ATM DVD 002 "Konserthuset").
- Circulated @ JPIO march 2006 as part of the "Swedish Masters" vine.

Warning - Womble gave me a warning message that this was a non DVD compliant resolution (544 x 576), 
which I think is a result of the resolution that ITV 2 broadcast at 
(I've had this warning before with ITV2 broadcasts).  So whilst it should play fine
on most DVD players, it may give problems on some fussy ones.

Someone asked me for this and I noticed it was on repeat so was happy to record it.  I think
ITV1 broadcasts at a higher bitrate, so I would be happy to see someone post the original broadcast 
as an upgrade.  I didn't tape the whole show by the way.  

Also, if anyone taped the Launch show from ITV2 in January I'd love to see Florence and the Machine's 
performance.

Notes:
Don't know what was going wrong on the night but KOL obviously felt they were not getting enough of a reaction from the crowd. It's a shame that they felt the need to end the show feeling angry as the performance itself seems pretty good to me. I really hope that Caleb didn't break that lovely old Gibson at the end of the set! Perhaps Reading's organisers should allow flags again next year?
The Reading footage has a maximum GOP length of 18 which is not strictly PAL specification and may cause problems with some standalones. If in doubt test with a DVD-RW first.
The V Festival footage was re-encoded from SATV resolution so that I could finally find a place to put it. If Reencoded footage is a no-no for you, skip VOB 3 and reauthor. If you already have or don't want T In The Park, skip VOB 2 and reauthor.

Broadcast: 	BBC HD 23.50-00.50 5th November 2010, http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00vtz9f 
	 	
Joining Jools on the eighth show of the series are Kings of Leon, Eric Clapton, MIA, The Vaccines, Jonathan Jeremiah, and English folk band Bellowhead. 

"Kings of Leon join Jools in the studio for the eighth live show of this series.They perform tunes from their new album, Come Around Sundown, the follow-up to their multi-platinum award winning breakthrough Only By the Night.

Eric Clapton plays tracks from his current album Clapton, which sees him paying tribute to the songs that inspired him early in his career.

MIA also joins Jools, with a couple of songs from her recent long player. Brand new UK band The Vaccines perform, with their blend of Beach Boys meets The Ramones pop tunes. There's also English folk band Bellowhead, the eleven piece band bought together by John Spiers and Jon Boden. Plus a debut performance from Jonathan Jeremiah, the London born singer songwriter who has been gaining comparisons with Cat Stevens."

From original torrent:

Don Kirshner's was not "performed" in Australia.  Rather it was shown on TV there and is the source for most, if not all copies, of that video.   It was aired on a show called Nightmoves, I believe.  

YCAWASM - ie Kirshner's - was recorded around June/July '76 as Joe's "farewell" to his solo career.  Felder plays throughout and the guitar interplay between Walsh and Felder is amazing.  The whole band is on fire - Willie Weeks and Andy Newmark, for example, had played on a ton of stuff together and were really at the top of their game at this time.

Notes:

No menu, chapter marks at the beginning of each track.

This was recorded onto Sky+ HD by my brother-in-law and I dumped it onto DVD when I visited him in July.  There is small bit 
of noise at the base of the picture in the bottom couple of lines of the picture which is a bit distracting if you watch it 
on a 4:3 screen with a letterbox - its worse for the first 5 or so minutes, then is barely noticeable.  I don't know
what caused this, but when I had another go at transferring it last weekend I got the same thing, so maybe it was present 
on the broadcast.  It does not show up when played back onto my 16:9 40" TV or my brother-in-law's 16:9 32" TV.

NIRVANA

Seattle, WA, USA

NTSC Format

Transferred by: Jim Hirte

     Video: 8mb/s CBR (NTSC)
     Audio: PCM (WAV)


SETLIST:
 
1. Radio Friendly Unit Shifter 
2. Drain You 
3. Breed 
4. Serve The Servants 
5. Rape Me 
6. Heart-Shaped Box 
7. Pennyroyal Tea 
8. Scentless Apprentice 
9. Lithium 
10. Jam -> Set Destruction 


NOTES:

Missing numerous songs. 

Notes: This broadcast includes the angel decapitation but does not 
include the end feedback. It has stereo audio.

Review: This is the commonly aired show known as "MTV Live And Loud". 
There are excellent shots all around on this DVD. The picture and audio
quality are both superb which makes this a great quality DVD. 

Additional notes: 

This is one of the wildest shows by Nirvana broadcast on MTV for New Year's 
Eve in 1993, and could easily be the considered the antithesis to the band's
Unplugged performance in New York recorded earlier on 11/18/1993 at Sony Studios. 

Kurt, with ex-Germ's guitarist, Pat Smear, who was hired by the band because 
Kurt feared he would lose his place in the middle of songs on tour, along with 
Krist Novoselic on Bass guitar, and Dave Grohl on drums offer up one of their 
most notable performances of late 1993. Kurt's vocals are absolutely blistering. 
The band feeds off of the audience's energy which is quickly whipped into a frenzy
with Kurt's usual set opener: "Radio Friendly Unit Shifter" which is anything but 
radio friendly, followed by the raucous, and at times, atonal gems that come
after such as "Scentless Apprentice," in which Kurt switches stomp pedals routinely 
on guitar for his guitar solos and add to the chaos of the song which was co-written
by Dave and Krist.


Set itself is very well lit, allowing for excellent close-ups of all 
4 band members with the "In Utero" backdrop. 

This source and transfer appear to be the sharpest in regards to video 
and sound quality of all circulating transfers for this set/venue. Because
there are cameramen everywhere, the camera work is phenomenal, and the audio 
lives up to its name: Loud!!!!!

Notes by Kris Sproul: 

Here's an upgraded DVDR of SNL 93 from the original broadcast. 
After some investigation, it appears that this is also a gen lower than
the PRO #1 on Chris Hill's DVD that circulated a while back. It turns out
that the tape he was working from had the same cuts as mine, and also 
included at least some of the same filler (such as the 09/08/93 clips).
I had also questioned the gen a while back, when I realized that his tape
may have come from someone with an old list in which things recorded from 
TV were "masters," as I believe that's how his was labeled (making it an
actual TV>VHS(2)). Regardless, it's clear that his came from a copy of the
tape I used, due to the same exact cuts and content, and I know for sure 
that the person I borrowed the tape from taped this all straight from TV 
himself, so this one should definitely be a gen better than Chris's version.
It's also sharper and nicer looking overall, in my opinion.

I've also included a few extras, including the 09/08/93 clips, 
an MTV interview of the band when In Utero came out, and an ABC In Concert 
clip with Krist talking about Rock The Vote.

The menu probably looks familiar, as I used the one from my SNL 92 DVD with 
slight modifications. I figured I'd keep the same theme, plus it made it easy.

Notes:
This is the broadcast version of Pearl Jam Unplugged.  So it doesn't have the two extra songs that are on the unedited production tape that is circulating....but, it also doesn't have the annoying black time code bar across the screen that is on that version.
I taped this back in 1992 upon it's first airing on eMpTy Vee.
The two commercial breaks were "edited" out during the taping with the good ol' pause button.
It was recorded on HiFi Stereo VHS.  Transferred straight from this tape to DVD.
The 15+ year old tape had aged well, so both sound and picture are EX.
There is one moment during "State Of Love..." where the HiFi track fails, and the audio becomes "normal" mono vhs audio, lasting about 3 seconds.  Any other fluctuations in picture or audio are very, very minor.
There must be other copies of this circulating, and the only reason I'm putting this out there is because I was seeing requests for a high quality copy without the time code....and this fits that bill.
Enjoy.
  -IV

Notes:
First thing to note is that the set comes on two seperate discs. Download one, download the other, download both or neither, the choice is yours! The reason for this is the resolution of the DVB-C transport stream for the V Festival footage. I couldn't figure out a way to put both shows to one disc without re-encoding the footage. If anyone has a clue please enlighten us :) 

This leads to the second note. To author the odd resolution V Fest footage, IFOEdit was used. This will mean Mac users with Toast may find their software goes into a sulk. Try LiquidCD?

*** Third note. The V Fest footage *IS NOT TO DVD SPECS*. It has been tested on several rigs and works with a LiteOn standalone, a Matsui and upscales superbly for such a small disc on a Toshiba HD player. My old Pioneer DV340 plays the show OK but only in a portion of the screen. Very odd. If in doubt try rewriteables first!

The short passage of time has meant that I have stupidly forgotten to keep a note of each individual lineage for the T in the Park tracks. Sorry about that but I was only putting the disc together for my own use until I realised how little Prodigy video seems to be out there. If I figure out which is which, I'll amend the announce ;)

A truly superb and exciting live band. These shows are very similar in content and intensity. Dance band, Techno, hard rock? I've no idea but I really wish there was more of this stuff about. Enjoy :D

*Caution*
Contains a little strobing and some language which delicate flowers may find offensive.
Scottish crowd may contain nuts.

Rage Against the Machine
1993-04-03
Cabaret Metro
Chicago, IL

Mary Morello Intro
Take The Power Back
Bombtrack
Fistful Of Steel
Bullet In The Head
Darkness of Greed
Wake Up
Jam w/ lyrics
Freedom

Holy shit... this is an ultra-rare recording that just happened to surface a month or so ago. Many, many, thanks to Aphydro and Ratmfan105 for hooking me up with this show. This is the first, full length pro shot of them to surface, so this is really special. The sound and visual quality is incredible- easily the best proshot of them to surface prior to 1996 (Pinkpop gives it a run for the money). The story behind this recording is that Aphydro found it on ebay and bought it- guy had no idea what he had. The only downside to this video is that there is a running timer on the bottom, but no big deal. I cannot state enough how lucky the community is to have this show- please share and enjoy!!!

Visit the ultimate Rage resource at downrodeo.org and their awesome forums at downrodeo.org/forums . My trading page can be found at db.etree.org/thomascirca and you can find the Rage media server at ragebootlegs.zapto.org .

Aphydro and Ratmfan105 are looking for videos from 7/30/11 (LA Rising), so if anyone has videos from that show please let me know! I flew out across the country to go- greatest Rage show so far. Many thanks to the tapers of the audio recordings that have surfaced here!

There's some nice footage of him arguing with security and repeatedly shouting "I didn't do anything!" which is really hilarious. Otherwise, fantastic sound and fantastic video.

---- Coachella 10-10-1999.txt ----
Rage Against The Machine
10/10/1999 Coachella Music Festival
Indio, CA, USA

Pro-Shot > Trade > TMPGEnc DVD Author 3 (no recode) > Sitting in my PC > You
Vid NTSC 4:3
Audio AC3
Length 59 minutes
Quality A or A-, depends on who you ask
Pro-shot, but it's clean: no logo and no breaks between songs. 
File created late at night on 4/26/2007 (T minus 3 days till Rage's return)

Setlist goes down like this:
01. Testify
02. Guerrilla Radio
03. Bombtrack
04. People Of The Sun
05. Know Your Enemy (Feat. Maynard From Tool)
06. Born Of A Broken Man
07. Bullet In The Head
08. Sleep Now In The Fire
09. No Shelter
10. Bulls On Parade
11. Killing In The Name 

It's a fantastic show; they were one of the headliners for this, the very first Coachella. I'm uploading this to commemorate Rage's big return this weekend also at the Coachella Festival: April 29th, 2007. It's been a long-ass time coming, I'm waiting on them to te-e-e-e-ear that shit up! Big, big ups to the original taper, WHEREVER you may be! Big ups also to my good buddy Paul "Duby" Dubczuk for the artwork as it is on the menu. Bad-ass shit if I've ever seen anything.

A PILLAR OF JUSTICE IS A KILLER OF PROGRESS

Vale and health to you all.

~~~Salva Veritate (Saving the Truth)

This is an excellent look at Rolling Stone Magazine, 
as told by the people who were there.  No live music 
in this - just the stories and photographs deemed
essential by the producers of this documentary marking
the magazines 25th anniversary.  This tale is a time 
capsule of very heavy times - veiled as a special
about a magazine covering Rock & Roll.  The challenge 
of making this ambitious project succeed was accomplished 
by framing the stories in a non-linear way.  
Specific aspects were highlighted by relevance in an

items.Notes:
---- SP RAR10 Lineage.txt ----
Smashing Pumpkins
20100826 Auditorio Nacional Mexico City MX


01 Today
02 Ava Adore
03 A Song for a Son
04 Eye
05 That's the Way (my Love is)
06 Tonight tonight
07 Stand inside your Love
08 Disarm (interrupted by Mexican Wrestlers)
09 Zero

This is a censored broadcast (At one time Billy says f*** and you hear the BEEP, Voice muted at Ava Adore's "You will always be my wh***", though at first listening I thought Billy is just too far to the mic because you can still hear the word, just very silent. It's not that distracting) Also, there are some german subtitles while Billy's talking (not during the songs).

I'm in it for the music, so I try to get the sound sources lossless. In this case I recorded the digital broadcast to get the best picture quality, additionally I recorded the analog audio broadcast to get the best audio quality. When I listen to the outcome I know it's worth it.

video source: MTV Austria (MTV live) DVB-S broadcast

audio source: MTV Germany analog satellite broadcast  (MTV live) / Kathrein UDF 420 receiver / Digidesign Digi003 / Sound Studio / Harddisk

Edited out commercials of video in MPEG Streamclip without reencoding. I recorded from MTV Austria instead of MTV Germany as MTV Austria broadcasts DVD compatible standards, whereas MTV Germany does not. 

Audio source was recorded in 96 khz and 32 bit. I had to do some slight speed correction on my analog recordings because otherwise the analog and digital sources wouldn't stay in sync. I told Sound Studio to assume 95996.46 Hz instead of 96kHz, then converted that to 48kHz 24bit.

Audio source was edited in ProTools and exported at 48 khz 16 bit. Slight eq used. 

DVD authored in DVD Studio Pro.

items.Setlist: tonight tonight; zero; an ode to no one; today; to forgive; bullet with butterfly wings; thru the eyes of ruby; porcelain of the vast oceans; disarm; muzzle; cherub rock; x. y. u
items.Notes:
---- SP DD 96 lineage.txt ----
Smashing Pumpkins
Philipshalle Dsseldorf Germany 
7th April 1996

tracklist:

tonight tonight
zero
an ode to no one
today
to forgive
bullet with butterfly wings
thru the eyes of ruby
porcelain of the vast oceans
disarm
muzzle
cherub rock
1979
x. y. u.

PAL 4:3
PCM stereo audio

source:
TV - recorded with a Panasonic NV-FS88 in SP Mode on S-VHS Maxell XR-S Black 240 tape. Can't remember if master or first generation S-VHS.

video lineage:

Playback for digitalization was on the same NV-FS88 into a MiroVideo DC30 (in a Mac G4 1,25 Ghz Dual with DC30 Xact Driver from Squared5) and recorded in MyVCR with uncompressed 10bit codec. From there I cut out announcers and stuff and cut off the fuzzy edges in MPEG Streamclip and save it once again in uncompressed 10bit. Then converted in progressive m2v-files. (filled the cut out lines with black lines to get PAL standard pixels again)

audio lineage:

S-VHS Audio got into a Digi003 audio interface and recorded at 96khz 32bit. Exported as 95994 Hz (no conversion, just changing the samplerate) and then converted to 24bit 48kHz for matching to video (I don't know why there is a tempo mismatch, but there is, and this procedure is my way of speed correction). Eq'd, de-essed and peak limited in ProTools, exported as 16bit 48khz.

This is a capture of the actual live broadcast at the performing date. There are some screen texts rolling to announce a phone number that you could have called back then, I think later broadcasts don't have these. Some might find these distracting, some might find them funny.

Have fun and all that

Smashing Pumpkins
1990 - 2003 compilation

Transfer: Magnavox ZV427MG9 Standalone > DVDr > DVD Shrink 2.3 (removed generic SA menu, no re-encoding)

01. Rhinoceros early/alternate video (1990)
-shot for a school project by a friend of the band
-contains B&W footage from an unknown show at Metro in late 1989 or early 1990
-audio track is the Reel Time Sessions (non-organ) version
sourced from unknown gen VHS, 6 minutes

02. In Concert: New Artist Profile (late 1991)
-backstage full-band interview, live clips from Gish release show on 6/22/91 (Rocket) and the porch show from 10/26/91 (Blue, Godzilla)
sourced from unknown gen VHS, 5 minutes

03. Chicago local news report (March 1995)
-band interview and clips from 666 (God, Zero) and 2/28/95 (Lily)
-different footage from the MTV News Report on the Double Door shows
sourced from unknown gen VHS, 4 minutes

04. Eurockennes Festival, Belfort, FR (1997/07/04)
-Bullet with Butterfly Wings, 1979, X.Y.U.
sourced from 2nd gen VHS, 13 minutes

05. TFI Friday (1998/05/22 - Riverside Studios, London, UK
-Ava Adore
sourced from unknown gen VHS, 5 minutes

06. MCM Special - "Le Mag" (1998/06/05 - Canal+ Studios, Paris, FR)
-Pug, Ava Adore, lengthy Billy interview (French subs)
-songs not available on other versions of this show
sourced from a 2nd gen VHS, 35 minutes

07. MuchMusic Argentina Special - "The Wedge" (1998/08/21 - Buenos Aires, AR)
-songs from early show (Perfect) and late show (Ava Adore, 1979) interspersed with a D'arcy interview (Spanish subs)
sourced from a 1st gen VHS, 21 minutes

08. This Week in Baseball (2003/03/28 - Parker Meridien Hotel, New York, NY)
-Billy and Jimmy interview, broadcast May 17th on This Week in Baseball
-clips from 2003/01/27
sourced from master VHS taped by Matt Krueger, 4 minutes

720 x 480 NTSC
256k AC3 audio (stereo)

no menu, auto chapters
thanks to Josh Provost and Matt Krueger for sending me their tapes to transfer

Don't sell, etc
-rhinowing

still playing "Once in a Lifetime", a CD track playing as audio and no credits 
at the end. That's why I list "Once in a Lifetime" as (audio cuts out). I think 
MusiquePlus fixed the end before a rebroadcast the day after, but I dont know if 
"Once in a Lifetime" ends in a different way. MusiquePlus probably rebroadcasted 
the show without the interviews too (as they often did for shows like that), but

This transfer is from a studio VHS. The video in this tape is free of
watermarks.

Unfortunately the tape cuts out after the first couple minutes of Rock On.

There is a blip in the tape, during `To Sheila', that has been edited out. The
signal stops for a second and then resumes from the point in the video a few
seconds before it cut out. This made it possible to edit out seamlessly.

The mix of footage used on this tape appears to be different from other versions
currently circulating. So, although some video already circulates, it is not the
same.

Thanks to Cool As Ice Cream for sending me his tapes to transfer.

Enjoy.

- magikarp99

---- The Smashing Pumpkins - Holland 1994-1995.txt ----
The Smashing Pumpkins - Holland 1994-1995

- Pinkpop Festival, Landgraaf, NL 23-05-94
- Loladamusica special xx-12-95

Source information:
TV > VHS > HDD recorder > DVD+R > VIDEO_TS

DVD decrypted using DVD Decrypter
Menu created with TMPGEnc

********************************************************************
DO NOT ENCODE TO VCD OR SVCD (OR ANY LOSSY FORMAT) AND DO NOT SELL                           
********************************************************************

23-05-94 Pinkpop Festival, Landgraaf, NL

01. Rocket
02. Today (cut)
03. Disarm
05. Hummer
06  Drown
07. Geek USA
08. Silverfuck
    > Over the Rainbow


Notes:

-During the first few seconds of rocket there is a presenter telling about what you can see in the broadcast later that evening. You can already hear the pumpkins start Rocket at the back of him, so I left him in. 
-Today is cut because the broadcast of the pinkpop festival was interrupted for other programs. At the end of today you can see the end credits of the broadcast.
-The very first notes of Disarm are cut. This is the way it was broadcasted. 
-The transition from drown into hummer is missing a part. Drown was not broadcasted until a few years after the festival and to make the show more complete I have included it in the place where it belonged in the setlist. The pumpkins went straight into hummer and a little part of that transition is missing due to 2 different broadcasts.

********************************************************************

xx-12-95 Loladamusica special

This is a special about the pumpkins from 1995 and was recorded around the time of the show they did at the Melkweg december 12th 1995. 
The special consists of interview parts with live songs inbetween. 

These songs are in the special:
- Bullet with butterfly wings (12-12-95) (last part cut)
- Thru the eyes of Ruby (12-12-95) (cut in two parts with interview segment inbetween)
- Today (23-05-94)
- Cherub Rock
- jellybelly

********************************************************************

Recorded, edited and uploaded to the Zomb april 2006 by Aadt.

Soundgarden - Oberhausen, Germany, 06 Sept 95, Turbinenhalle (HI 8 Master)

A Bobfather Recording !
SOURCE: SONY HI 8 video cam w/ external mic (aiwa cm 30 stereo mic;with an extra-built-in-resistor to avoid distorsion)
LINEAGE: SONY HI 8 Video cam > PIONEER STANDALONE DVD REKORDER (fine mode)> DVD (optimized mode)

Searching With My Good Eye Closed
Let Me Drown
Spoonman
My Wave
Drawing Flies
Ty Cobb
Fell on Black Days
Mailman
Head Down
Superunknown
Rusty Cage
Waiting For the Sun
Black Hole Sun
Jesus Christ Pose
4th of July
Kickstand
I Want You (She's So Heavy)

TRT: 80 min


This is a must have for every Soundgarden fan. I recorded it from the left sided balcony, which wasn`t open for the rest of the audience. I had the permission to film by one of the support bands (can`t remember the name)and nobody stopped me filming or kicked me off the balcony when Soundgarden hit the stage. So I decided to keep on filming. Good idea, eh ? Used a tripod and an external microphone. Supersteady `cause I was alone on the balcony. This shot is almost perfect. Little tiny white points from time to time `caused by the age of the tape or the tape itself, but if you have a problem with this you should visit a psychatrist soon ;).

Enjoy & share, but never sell (or you`ll burn in hell). Don`t convert into lossy formats !

Best
Bobfather

items.Notes:
---- setlist.txt ----
As you can see from the info. below I swapped in alternate audio for this. Not that the video
source is bad, in fact it is excellent. It's just that I think this vinyl source is really fantastic and sounds superior to the video source when played through good speakers such as
Vandersteens. So I would recommend that you do not judge the sound through your TV's
speakers. The audio was synched up perfectly throughout using Amadeus II. And since I
used alternate audio I went ahead and included all of the last song, which was faded out
during the credits on the original. To do this I re-used crowd and off-stage shots. The video
quality is flawless all the way through but isn't always all that sharp. I'd say it's pretty typical of a mid-eighties shot, still very good though. I rarely see anything from this era that is much better. I'd rate the video a borderline A+ and the audio an A+. There are proper chapters...

none of this 5-min. stuff. There is no menu... it auto starts.

items.Notes:
---- The Kinks - In Concert (BBC).txt ----
The Kinks - In Concert (BBC)


There are conflicting opinions as to where this show was filmed, and when it was first broadcast

Theory 1
Filmed at The Rainbow Theatre, Finsbury Park, London 1972-01-21
Shown on BBC TV on 1972-07-23
Repeated on 1973-01-24
Supported by db.etree http://db.etree.org/bs_d.php?year=1972&artist_key=8906 , Bootlegzone http://www.bootlegzone.com/album.php?name=tkkoh&section=42 etc


Theory 2
Filmed at BBC Televison Centre, London 1973-01-24
Broadcast on 1973-03-15
Supported by
1) The BBC referring to the show as being "from March 1973"
2) The BBC "Copyright 1973" sign at the end of the film (rather than "Copyright 1972")
3) Doug Hinman's book "The Kinks - All Day And All Of The Night" which lists The Kinks' activities from 1961 to 1996


it boils down to whether you believe the BBC or the bootleggers. What is not disputed is that I recorded this when it was shown as part of BBC Four's "1973 Week" on 2006-04-06

U.S. TV - "Don Kirshner's Rock Concert"

Excellent quality pre-broadcast source. Check the screen grabs and audio samples to get an idea of the quality. There are a few bad video frames but this is mostly stellar quality, both audio and video. I recommend this one highly!

Extensive web searching did not turn up any released material. 

1 Don Kirshner intro
2 Roxanne
3 Message In A Bottle
4 Can't Stand Losing You
5 Next To You
6 Walking On The Moon
7 The Bed's Too Big Without You
8 Deathwish
Total time: 34:05

Lineage & transfer [2007]: Low gen. pre-broadcast U-Matic tape > Super Beta Hi-Fi tape > Sony SL-HF450 > Sony DVMC-DA2 Media Converter > Apple Macintosh Final Cut Pro (nip and tuck edits, filter to replace bottom of screen "head switch jitter" with black and chaptering) > Compressor > DVD Studio Pro (menu/authoring) > VIDEO_TS file set. md5 file created with checkSUM+.

Audio post capture processing in Pro Tools (DC offset, normalization and fades). Audio placed back into Final Cut Pro before Compressor down-sampling. 

Video: NTSC 720x480 VBR 7.7 Mbps peak, 6.2 Mbps average data rate, 2-pass. 
Audio - choice of: Dolby Digital 2/0 (L,R), 48 kHz sample rate, 448 kbps data rate 
or 
Linear PCM (2 channel 48kHz 16 bit). (The audio is dual monophonic TV audio).

Notes from the web searching: After the show in Portland, Oregon on February 5th, 1980 and prior to the show in Honolulu on February 8th, The Police went to Los Angeles to record for the TV program "Don Kirshner's Rock Concert" before a live studio audience. Presumably this was recorded on the 6th, since they would not have flown the long distance to Honolulu on the same day that they were doing the show there. This appearance was broadcast on May 17, 1980.

Enjoy and SHARE!

---- Them CrookedVultures.txt ----
Austin City Limits is an American television music program and a staple of the Public Broadcasting Service. Austin City Limits was initially created with an eye and ear toward original Texas music, featuring artists that created innovative new sounds in everything from western swing and Texas blues to Tejano music, progressive country and rock n' roll. The series went on to feature a wide range of American roots artists, covering a variety of styles and expanding beyond the borders of the Lone Star State. As the programs audience has grown, the music has encompassed regional, national and even international performers, and producer Terry Lickona continues to seek a balance of music genres in every new season. Austin City Limits today focuses on the unique contributions of diverse artists, music and songwriting from around the world.

First aired in 1976, Austin City Limits has become American television's longest-running concert music program. The program is taped live by PBS member station KLRU on the campus of the University of Texas at Austin. Images of Austin, Texas, the self-proclaimed "Live Music Capital of the World," are seen in the opening credits. ACL's set also features a mock skyline of Austin. The show inspired the Austin City Limits Music Festival, an annual live music festival at Zilker Park in Austin.

This Episode
Josh Homme from Queens of the Stone Age, Dave Grohl from the Foo Fighters and John Paul Jones from Led Zeppelin combine for high volume rock n roll.

NOTES:

The BBC broadcast the complete set in two parts on BBC Two on the
night of the festival.  The first half (tracks 1-10) was broadcast
live, and the second half was broadcast delayed later that evening.

The second half was broadcast live on BBC Three, but with a short
break for the news headlines and an incomplete version of track 11.  

In addition, highlights from the set were broadcast on BBCi later that
evening.

This recording consists mainly of the two BBC Two broadcasts.  The
first broadcast ended a few notes into "Hardest Button", and the
second broadcast started a few seconds before the start of that track
- so there was a perfect splice point without any lost footage.

The BBC Three broadcast showed an extra 25 seconds of the White Stripes
leaving the stage at the end of the set, which I have spliced onto the
end of the BBC Two broadcast.

Sunday 29 October 2006
Main Space, Roundhouse

The Who - BBC Electric Proms 06 & BBC One Sessions present

Series of unique, intimate performances by some of the greatest legends and contemporary stars around. Pete Townshend and Roger Daltrey are on blistering form in a session recorded at the Roundhouse , as the grand finale of the BBC's Electric Proms.

The band proceed to rattle off hit after hit as well as performing the world premiere of their brand new mini opera 'Wire & Glass'.

"Baba O'Riley" and an extended version of "My Generation" really get the crowd in the party mood while Zac Starkey, Ringo Star's son, performs brilliantly on a Keith Moon-esque double drum kit. Daltrey spins himself and his mic around on a wonderful "Pinball Wizard" while Pete Townshend proves he can still cut the mustard with some fantastic guitar playing on "My Generation" and "See Me, Feel Me".

By the end it's clear this is more than just a gig, it's a musical extravaganza that provides a fitting finale to the inaugural BBC Electric Proms.

General-Notes:
This was one of the last shows Zwan played. Too bad, cause i had tickets for the Gurten-Festival in Switzerland they should have played some weeks later...so that's why i haven't seen them live ;(
Anyway, i recorded this show when it was first aired. It seems that other recordings also exist. I have no clue whether they look better than mine (DVB would be nice), but they don't sound better. That's for sure (see Audio-Notes). So if anyone who downloaded my version could tell me if there's a better quality recording out there, i'd be happy.....


Transfer-Notes:
Some of you guys may ask: "Why did he downsize it? That's a loss of quality!" Well, you are wrong there...
When i recorded the show onto DVD with FR mode, it gave me the highest bitrate that's possible (about 10Mbps for Audio&Video). But the WDR broadcasts are usually about 4000kbps (experience from other DVD's that were directly recorded on HD). So if i shared the 10Mbps version, that would have been the same thing like you'd reencode mp3 to Wav. Makes no sense at all, quality don't get better....but the size of the file gets much bigger. So i decided to downsize to VBR 6000kbps (just a safety. Minimum was set to 4500kbps, maximum to 7000kbps), Hope you can live with that.....


Audio-Notes:
As always, i'm trying to give you guys and girls the best possible quality (said: trying ;) ). So i thought: if i do this DVD then it needs the best available audio. And that is....mighty Mixwell's 13RM of course. Damn, that was hard fight to synch the audio & video. It was like hell...terrible. Did i mention it was hard work? Ok, finally it worked. Below you can see Mixwell's notes on his remaster. So there shouldn't be any questions left.


As always...ENJOY

Obertu (aka Sakul)

PS: Big thank goes out to Mixwell. I love your work. Thank u so much!!!
(The ones that don't respect his work: go fuck yourself!)

_________________________________________________________________________________________
Mixwell's Notes:

"This one was difficult, to say the least. I worked on it a few times over the last 3 or 4 months. I had a source of it that I got from the newsgroups maybe three weeks after the show, and no source info. It sounded nice, but much like a digital FM source or even more likely a digital TV broadcast, as at times I hear an 18k TV tube interference. Digital FM or TV is something which I consider to be more of a lossy format. It's an encoded process anyway, and if MP3's or WMA's are considered lossy, then so should these as it's a very similar process. It's nice that it didn't start out lossless, then lossy, then back. But let's face it, it ain't lossless the way an old dog like me expects his lossless to be. Yea, I'm not a big fan of the digital FM or TV. Woof.

Then Obertu sent us his lossless TV rip. Ouch! That one is crunched. Heavily. But contains certain elements that mine lacked. Combining them is tricky, but I did it anyway. I had to play with it often, abandon it, try again a different way, then abandon again. When combining two sources of identical origin (the TV broadcast in this case) phasing issues come to the forefront real quick.
